{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01JCXVRkGFp78FeJ3Fhe8xEF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of the setup. Let me understand:\n\n1. There's an Elasticsearch cluster running in the `elasticsearch` namespace\n2. There's a TLS secret `es-http-tls` with the current CA and leaf certificate\n3. There's a `es-http-ca` ConfigMap with the current CA cert\n4. There's a `es-http-old` ConfigMap with the OLD CA cert and old fingerprints (same as current - this is the precondition state)\n\nThe task is:\n- Rotate the HTTP CA and leaf certificates with minimal downtime\n- New certs must be valid for ~1 year\n- Clients need to trust the new CA\n- No CRDs or ECK operator involved\n\nThe oracle will verify that the `es-http-tls` secret contains new certificates with different fingerprints than what's in `es-http-old`, the `es-http-ca` ConfigMap has been updated with the new CA, the cluster remains accessible over HTTPS, and the new certificate has roughly a year of validity remaining.\n\nCurrently, the CA and leaf certificate are signed by `CN=es-ca` and valid until June 25, 2027. The `es-http-old` ConfigMap holds the old CA and fingerprints as a baseline reference—after rotation, these should diverge.\n\nI need to check what tools are available in the `openssl-toolbox` pod, then generate a new CA with a one-year validity period, create a new leaf certificate signed by it, update the `es-http-tls` secret with the new certs, and update the `es-http-ca` ConfigMap so clients can validate against the new CA. I should also investigate whether Elasticsearch supports hot certificate reloading or if a rolling restart is necessary to minimize downtime.\n\nI need to check how Elasticsearch is configured to use TLS—specifically whether it's mounting the secret as a volume so it can pick up cert changes dynamically.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":nu